We don't have to do this in Node. Instead we can put NGINX or Apache in front of the backend as a reverse proxy and have one of them deal with TLS, they'll just talk to the backend via regular HTTP.

This looks to be a problem with indexing. When inserting tweets into the database, we first check that the tweet does not already exist in the db, causing the backend to search through a bunch of unindexed fields many times. I've indexed the `embed_id` field of the Tweet schema and restarted the server for now.

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/11730903/23310974/6a6d147c-fa82-11e6-8de2-42b95e493dfd.png)

This doesn't seem to be an issue anymore after the recent API update and changes.

f880d6a81b5c64244133799aefeff429e6f48487 Limits tweets analyzed to English only.

Detecting if trends are English or Spanish is harder, but should be pretty rare from now on so I'm closing this. May have to reopen if trends in other languages start to crop up more. 

Also, if we need to detect the language of a tweet, we don't need to use another package, the Twitter API already gives us that information (https://dev.twitter.com/overview/api/tweets) (scroll down to the 'lang' field)
I haven't observed this for a while so closing, if this comes up again in the future I'll look into it.
